203
00:16:01.830 --> 00:16:06.370
It may go deeper than Hollywood though. Compare
Japanese mythological storytelling conventions

204
00:16:06.370 --> 00:16:10.629
to ‘western’ ones. Modern stories, in
one way or another, are always constructed

205
00:16:10.629 --> 00:16:15.300
on the foundation of ancient mythological
cycles. For this, European stories were made

206
00:16:15.300 --> 00:16:19.339
on a tradition stemming from Roman and Greek
poems, as well as Abrahamic parables.

207
00:16:19.339 --> 00:16:24.310
In either case, the narrative convention of
these styles very much lean towards the explicit.

208
00:16:24.310 --> 00:16:28.779
Dialogue is over-rought, clear in it’s delivery,
with the intention to convey complete meaning

209
00:16:28.779 --> 00:16:32.920
in the spoken word alone. Though… it’s
really hit or miss with that. Turns out that

210
00:16:32.920 --> 00:16:38.699
after 2500 years of the bible, some of the
old meaning has been lost in translation.

211
00:16:38.699 --> 00:16:42.720
European theatrical conventions also focused
exclusively on an actor’s ability to deliver

212
00:16:42.720 --> 00:16:48.300
lines, and what the lines themselves say.
In the Elizabethan era, it was common to simply

213
00:16:48.300 --> 00:16:52.959
not have a set or props for a given production.
And so, some of you may have noticed that

214
00:16:52.959 --> 00:16:57.259
Shakespeare goes to great lengths to have
his actors describe what a given set looks

215
00:16:57.259 --> 00:17:02.089
like, what the weather is like, how dark it
is. The responsibility of the actors was not

216
00:17:02.089 --> 00:17:07.140
to show this via acting, but telling via dialogue.
They couldn’t really afford to “show don’t

217
00:17:07.140 --> 00:17:08.820
tell” until film came along.

218
00:17:08.820 --> 00:17:13.209
Compare and contrast to a Japanese performance
art like Kabuki… which has markedly less

219
00:17:13.209 --> 00:17:18.170
dialogue and which the audience is more encouraged
to read into how a given performer is carrying

220
00:17:18.170 --> 00:17:23.930
themselves, their gestures, their expressions.
How they move. Why they move. A single look

221
00:17:23.930 --> 00:17:27.450
can mean as much as, or more than, a Shakespearean
sonnet.

222
00:17:27.450 --> 00:17:32.910
That’s why a lot of Western audiences really
don’t get why people love ballet and fashion.

223
00:17:32.910 --> 00:17:38.150
That’s ALL show and no tell. In both of
those cases — they are not seen as ‘accessable’

224
00:17:38.150 --> 00:17:41.560
because most people have not developed the
sensibilities needed to analyze how well a

225
00:17:41.560 --> 00:17:43.750
given balerina is pretending to be a swan.

226
00:17:43.750 --> 00:17:47.950
So yes, among Western audiences there is an
expectation that media will hold their hand

227
00:17:47.950 --> 00:17:52.390
and guide them through every element of the
plot. Thought process being ‘if the creator

228
00:17:52.390 --> 00:17:56.920
wants me to know about something in their
media, they will tell me that it is important.’

229
00:17:56.920 --> 00:18:01.110
Hitchcock famously got around this by SHOWING
you something important three times, but not

230
00:18:01.110 --> 00:18:06.470
necessarily talking about it even once. That
way it’s hard to miss but he’s not spilling

231
00:18:06.470 --> 00:18:09.330
the whole mystery for the viewers who are
actually paying attention.

232
00:18:09.330 --> 00:18:13.530
Conversely, the argument for nuance goes:
‘if the creator has something important

233
00:18:13.530 --> 00:18:18.490
to say in this media, they will reward me
by letting me figure it out for myself.’

234
00:18:18.490 --> 00:18:20.610
Basically the golden rule of David Lynch.

235
00:18:20.610 --> 00:18:24.910
Which way is better? Depends on the storyteller,
the story, and the audience.

236
00:18:24.910 --> 00:18:31.330
There’s actually been a centuries-long debate
within art criticism. Do we, as art critics,

237
00:18:31.330 --> 00:18:35.470
observe the work as it was intended, only
factoring in the cultural attitudes that the

238
00:18:35.470 --> 00:18:40.850
author was deliberately feeding into their
art. Or do we analyze in spite of the author’s

239
00:18:40.850 --> 00:18:45.810
intentions, factoring other iconographic connections
that the author was not necessarily intending,

240
00:18:45.810 --> 00:18:48.330
but that enriches the work nevertheless.

241
00:18:48.330 --> 00:18:53.190
Many authors, in biographies and interviews
will often speak to assumptions of their work:

242
00:18:53.190 --> 00:18:58.520
symbolic value, allegory, allusion — and
oftentimes they admit that what is being read

243
00:18:58.520 --> 00:19:02.970
into their work was never intended. For instance,
after being consistently questioned on the

244
00:19:02.970 --> 00:19:07.760
feminist power of Carrie, Stephen King admitted
that he had never intended for it to be viewed

245
00:19:07.760 --> 00:19:09.450
under such a feminist lens.

246
00:19:09.450 --> 00:19:14.150
Instead, he said that after reading his first
draft, he noticed a reoccurring pattern of

247
00:19:14.150 --> 00:19:19.050
blood. And in subsequent drafts, highlighted
these elements further. The result was a story

248
00:19:19.050 --> 00:19:24.410
which, under a certain interpretation, spoke
to a way that women find power because of

249
00:19:24.410 --> 00:19:25.870
and in spite of suffering.

250
00:19:25.870 --> 00:19:30.150
Does King’s lack of deliberate intention
diminish the art or the artist?

251
00:19:30.150 --> 00:19:34.220
I would argue: no. The ability for an artist
to focus on developing a good story, while

252
00:19:34.220 --> 00:19:39.540
subliminally including elements that speak
to a culture at large is an outstanding talent.

253
00:19:39.540 --> 00:19:48.220
And sadly, many who have this talent are often
plagued with lifelong inadequacy issues, imposter

254
00:19:48.220 --> 00:19:54.100
complexes, and frequently opt to give up before
they hit their stride because others hold

255
00:19:54.100 --> 00:20:04.120
them up against artists who appear to do it
all seamlessly… Those who, also, would have

256
00:20:04.120 --> 00:20:08.360
openly admitted to not having the slightest
clue what they’re doing, but happen to do

257
00:20:08.360 --> 00:20:11.210
the right thing so nobody bothers to ask.

258
00:20:11.210 --> 00:20:15.411
And in this respect, Yuri!!! On ICE exists
as a triumph of gay representation. Before

259
00:20:15.411 --> 00:20:20.420
it set out to do anything, it was going to
tell a good story. Where most stories function

260
00:20:20.420 --> 00:20:26.550
around telling people how to succeed, Yuri!!!
On ICE was primarily about how not to give

261
00:20:26.550 --> 00:20:29.520
up.

262
00:20:29.520 --> 00:20:35.470
Really, the nail in the coffin should have
been the direct message from the creator.

263
00:20:35.470 --> 00:20:39.080
“Yuri and Victor are gay, and in a relationship.”
She said that—

264
00:20:39.080 --> 00:20:42.870
So that really should be the end of it. We’re
not gonna do anything else to talk about why

265
00:20:42.870 --> 00:20:46.660
Victor and Yuri are queer. It’s a thing.
Be mad.

266
00:20:46.660 --> 00:20:51.250
But… Japan has certain laws, such as what
time of night a queer-centric show can be

267
00:20:51.250 --> 00:20:55.610
aired on TV. This show was slated for an earlier
timeslot in the night because its first a

268
00:20:55.610 --> 00:21:01.020
foremost a sports anime. In order for the
quiet part to be as loud as the creator wanted,

269
00:21:01.020 --> 00:21:06.670
it would have have to air much later at night
than the network wanted. Probably not reach

270
00:21:06.670 --> 00:21:11.220
as wide an audience because of it, and definitely
not have the same amount of advertising behind

271
00:21:11.220 --> 00:21:12.220
it.

272
00:21:12.220 --> 00:21:16.550
What the creator did with presenting an obviously
gay story while still appeasing the censorship

273
00:21:16.550 --> 00:21:23.370
regulations was… just an all round masterclass
in network trolling. She had a gay thing that

274
00:21:23.370 --> 00:21:27.850
was, more or less approved for all ages—

275
00:21:27.850 --> 00:21:33.110
—And wanted to project it out to as large
an audience as possible, while still preserving

276
00:21:33.110 --> 00:21:38.161
the queer elements of the story. So, she had
to compromise her artistic vision, appease

277
00:21:38.161 --> 00:21:43.540
the network demands, and develop a quality
program that would appeal to audiences.

278
00:21:43.540 --> 00:21:47.840
The easiest thing to do in this situation
would be to develop a token straight love

279
00:21:47.840 --> 00:21:52.420
interest for Yuri and/or Victor. That way,
with heterosexuality confirmed, the creator

280
00:21:52.420 --> 00:21:57.050
would have a lot more leeway from the studio
to do what she wanted. But instead, and I

281
00:21:57.050 --> 00:22:02.420
strongly approve of this, she coded elements
of queerness so strongly that they are absolutely

282
00:22:02.420 --> 00:22:06.860
unmissable, and yet, she can argue to the
network that it matches the straight-leaning

283
00:22:06.860 --> 00:22:11.090
sensibility of network standards.

284
00:22:11.090 --> 00:22:24.010
I don’t know how much you know about show
business but being able to do that without

285
00:22:24.010 --> 00:22:29.840
sacrificing the integrity of the project is
absolutely incredible. As a comparison of

286
00:22:29.840 --> 00:22:34.210
how things can go terribly wrong, Nickelodeon
fought tooth and nail against the creative

287
00:22:34.210 --> 00:22:39.970
team of Legend of Korra, who wanted to present
a queer woman of colour. Which were, at the

288
00:22:39.970 --> 00:22:44.210
time, three words that the network did not
want to hear in a pitch.

289
00:22:44.210 --> 00:22:49.900
Unfortunately, for whatever reason, there
was little effort made to code Korra as ‘queer’

290
00:22:49.900 --> 00:22:54.050
— maybe it was even a studio note to force
Korra into a number of Love triangles with

291
00:22:54.050 --> 00:22:59.080
other men, and a continuing on-again-off-again
relationship with a male supporting character.

292
00:22:59.080 --> 00:23:04.880
Eventually going so far as to push the final
seasons of the show onto their web only platform

293
00:23:04.880 --> 00:23:10.270
because they knew Korra and Asami were going
to hold hands in the final shot and, well,

294
00:23:10.270 --> 00:23:12.740
we can’t put that on TV, now can we?

295
00:23:12.740 --> 00:23:16.380
And that isn’t to say that Yuri!!! On ICE
did not suffer it’s own managerial problems.

296
00:23:16.380 --> 00:23:21.640
There were insane deadlines on the animation
department so the skating scenes suffer from

297
00:23:21.640 --> 00:23:26.530
some painful frame drops, the script for each
episode was roughly twice as long as the network

298
00:23:26.530 --> 00:23:30.970
permitted, so a lot of character development
for smaller characters had to be dropped.

299
00:23:30.970 --> 00:23:36.150
And it very well may be that the more explicit
gay content had to be cut for time constrains

300
00:23:36.150 --> 00:23:37.770
as well as network appeasement.

301
00:23:37.770 --> 00:23:42.570
And yet, the creative team very masterfully
used the time resources they had to advance

302
00:23:42.570 --> 00:23:47.970
the already-constricted plot at the same time
as dropping some gay bombs. And, maybe even

303
00:23:47.970 --> 00:23:53.330
as a happy accident, used nuance to their
advantage to make queer content that benefitted

304
00:23:53.330 --> 00:23:57.270
from having no explicit discussion of homosexuality.

305
00:23:57.270 --> 00:24:02.720
Because Yuri!!! On ICE is not about queerness.
It’s about queer people, but it’s not

306
00:24:02.720 --> 00:24:08.441
about qualifying the validity of their personhood
based on their capacity for queerness. Their

307
00:24:08.441 --> 00:24:11.990
queerness is neither the first nor the second
thing that comes to mind when discussing their

308
00:24:11.990 --> 00:24:13.140
roles in the plot, and the roles they have
to other characters.

309
00:24:13.140 --> 00:24:16.320
This includes the relationship between Victor
and Yuri.

310
00:24:16.320 --> 00:24:20.620
And this isn’t to say you aren’t meant
to see the queerness, nor that this story

311
00:24:20.620 --> 00:24:25.100
is not meant to be seen as a love story. But
it is meant to say that the characters have

312
00:24:25.100 --> 00:24:30.500
a purpose beyond letting the audience know
that they’re here and they’re queer. Because,

313
00:24:30.500 --> 00:24:35.740
speaking from my experiences as a gay person,
I can safely say that ‘being gay’ is not

314
00:24:35.740 --> 00:24:39.900
what’s on my mind most of the time. I don’t
feel the need to qualify my gayness either

315
00:24:39.900 --> 00:24:44.700
to a partner, family or the rest of society.

316
00:24:44.700 --> 00:24:49.550
In the same way, Yuri and Victor do not need
to have an exchange that goes along the lines

317
00:24:49.550 --> 00:24:50.550
of:

318
00:24:50.550 --> 00:24:55.660
“But… I’m a boy like you! W-why are
you holding my hand!?!”

319
00:24:55.660 --> 00:25:01.260
“Ever since I was young… I knew I was
different… and I was drawn to you because…

320
00:25:01.260 --> 00:25:05.970
you’re also different — like I saw in
myself years ago!”

321
00:25:05.970 --> 00:25:09.440
They know they’re gay. They don’t need
to have a heart-to-heart about it because

322
00:25:09.440 --> 00:25:15.950
that does not benefit them, as characters.
Doing so is only to benefit an audience and

323
00:25:15.950 --> 00:25:19.410
would, as a result, break the emotional realism
of the scene.

324
00:25:19.410 --> 00:25:24.890
And in doing so this speaks to a queer experience
that is much more realistic, and identifiable.

325
00:25:24.890 --> 00:25:30.860
And so, by keeping the queerness coded — ironically
— this moves closer into an experience that

326
00:25:30.860 --> 00:25:36.770
is intended to be appreciated by queer people.
Rather than presenting a queer experience

327
00:25:36.770 --> 00:25:40.010
for the intention of being consumed by straight
people.

328
00:25:40.010 --> 00:25:46.000
In fact, the lack of clarity also affords
a, perhaps accidental instance of nonbinary

329
00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:51.210
representation, specifically from Yuri. As
per elements of the show, he is much more

330
00:25:51.210 --> 00:25:53.500
comfortable skating his programs as a woman.

331
00:25:53.500 --> 00:25:58.310
He spares no expense to clarify that he feels
like he doesn’t belong with the other men,

332
00:25:58.310 --> 00:26:03.450
and any time the word ‘man’ is used in
the entirety of the show, it is always in

333
00:26:03.450 --> 00:26:06.960
a period of great anxiety for Yuri himself.

334
00:26:06.960 --> 00:26:11.970
Victor also started out his career looking
very androgynous, bending the separation between

335
00:26:11.970 --> 00:26:19.950
male and female, if not shattering it.

336
00:26:19.950 --> 00:26:26.010
So at this point I ask myself — what is
the difference between representation, coding,

337
00:26:26.010 --> 00:26:32.350
pandering, and baiting? And is drawing a distinction
necessary? After all, it would be unfair to

338
00:26:32.350 --> 00:26:37.150
act like Yuri on Ice is the only piece of
media ever produced to have subtle queer representation.

339
00:26:37.150 --> 00:26:41.670
The problem is that in most other cases, the
representation isn't so much subtle as it

340
00:26:41.670 --> 00:26:46.290
is simply not acknowledged. It would be easy
to just drop my series of queer baiting videos

341
00:26:46.290 --> 00:26:50.520
right here, but there’s been a few movies
that have come out since then that I’d rather

342
00:26:50.520 --> 00:26:55.750
talk about. We’ll drop them into two categories.
Queer representation, and Queer Pandering.

343
00:26:55.750 --> 00:26:57.470
See if you can tell which is which.

344
00:26:57.470 --> 00:26:59.090
Disney’s Cruella.

345
00:26:59.090 --> 00:27:02.860
I wasn’t sure what to expect from Cruella,
to be honest. Disney was already trumpeting

346
00:27:02.860 --> 00:27:07.170
it as their “First Out Gay Character”,
the third or forth such character in the last

347
00:27:07.170 --> 00:27:12.620
few years, so I was preparing myself for a
big ole eye roll. But it never came. 

348
00:27:12.620 --> 00:27:16.990
The gay character in question, Arty, a fashionista
who helps Cruella create her devilish looks

349
00:27:16.990 --> 00:27:21.280
throughout the film, didn’t silently pine
over any of the male characters, wasn’t

350
00:27:21.280 --> 00:27:25.300
abused for his queerness, and didn’t exist
just to give Cruella someone to talk to. He

351
00:27:25.300 --> 00:27:29.290
was active in the plot, helping her create
the looks she would use to bring down her

352
00:27:29.290 --> 00:27:34.610
rival The Baronesse, performs live on stage
at an impromptu Cruella fashion show, and

353
00:27:34.610 --> 00:27:38.400
isn’t just forgotten when the plot moves
past him. In the closing scenes of the film

354
00:27:38.400 --> 00:27:43.950
he’s among Cruella’s crew. Jasper and
Horace are there, of course, but so is Arty.

355
00:27:43.950 --> 00:27:47.670
Meaning he’s probably coming back for the
sequel Disney currently has in development.

356
00:27:47.670 --> 00:27:52.290
Now plenty of queer people have pointed out
that it’s never stated in that he is in

357
00:27:52.290 --> 00:27:57.840
fact gay, which is true. But he’s pure camp,
with his Bowie inspired looks, and even talks

358
00:27:57.840 --> 00:28:02.440
about being beaten up for being different.
He doesn’t say he’s gay, or show romantic

359
00:28:02.440 --> 00:28:06.890
interest in any other characters, but nobody
does. Though Jasper might have a crush on

360
00:28:06.890 --> 00:28:10.560
Cruella, she doesn’t seem to reciprocate,
and it could easily be read a brother/sister

361
00:28:10.560 --> 00:28:14.750
type of situation. Jasper’s heterosexuality
is just as subtle as Arty’s homosexuality.

362
00:28:14.750 --> 00:28:20.010
Cruella, on the other hand, never even gives
a longing look to anything that isn’t fabric.

363
00:28:20.010 --> 00:28:24.720
Leading me to believe that maybe, just maybe,
Cruella might fall onto the ACE spectrum.

364
00:28:24.720 --> 00:28:28.950
Which, if she was still a puppy killer would
be pretty bad ACE representation. But as it

365
00:28:28.950 --> 00:28:33.140
seems she’s reformed her ways from Disney’s
last version of her to this one, she’s less

366
00:28:33.140 --> 00:28:35.970
bad guy and more bad ass. 

367
00:28:35.970 --> 00:28:40.810
So the queerness is Cruella is subtle, and
does require the audience to understand at

368
00:28:40.810 --> 00:28:44.750
least a bit of the history of camp and androgyny,
but it’s some of the better queer rep I’ve

369
00:28:44.750 --> 00:28:49.050
seen in a mainstream Hollywood movie, especially
from Disney. I’m sure they’ll eliminate

370
00:28:49.050 --> 00:28:52.390
my current good will once they release that
River Cruise movie though. 

371
00:28:52.390 --> 00:28:54.510
Next!
Ah, more Disney. 

372
00:28:54.510 --> 00:28:56.380
BEAUTY AND THE BEAST.

373
00:28:56.380 --> 00:28:58.820
The live action one.

374
00:28:58.820 --> 00:29:04.120
Now this ones been discussed to death. LeFou,
the gay under our microscope here, is just

375
00:29:04.120 --> 00:29:09.200
bad representation. Firstly, his name literally
means “The Fool”, so hurray us. Secondly,

376
00:29:09.200 --> 00:29:13.260
he pines after the biggest jock in town, whose
an absolute asshole to everyone including

377
00:29:13.260 --> 00:29:17.390
him. As if we never grow out the bad habits
we pick up in grade school. His character

378
00:29:17.390 --> 00:29:21.390
is a villain until he’s suddenly not. When
