435
00:33:48.370 --> 00:33:56.910
inside. Data that, when read, would reveal
him in compromised positions. And his dick

436
00:33:56.910 --> 00:33:57.910
pics. 

437
00:33:57.910 --> 00:33:58.910
I’m not kidding. 

438
00:33:58.910 --> 00:34:02.930
Black Mask, or Roman Sianos, was a bit of
a kinky bottom you see. And heaven help the

439
00:34:02.930 --> 00:34:06.350
woman who let that info leak out to the rest
of Gotham’s underworld.

440
00:34:06.350 --> 00:34:11.129
But WB got cold feet and called for reshoots.
Simplifying the plot and vaguely straight

441
00:34:11.129 --> 00:34:15.950
washing Roman and his serial killing henchman
/ dom top, Victor Zazz. Oh the movie we could

442
00:34:15.950 --> 00:34:17.520
have had if it weren’t for corporate meddling.

443
00:34:17.520 --> 00:34:22.850
But the queerness of the couple is still abundantly
clear. Roman never says he’s queer but when

444
00:34:22.850 --> 00:34:26.310
he’s rocking a pink silk kimono while dancing
around with a martini, I don’t think it

445
00:34:26.310 --> 00:34:27.480
needs be remarked. 

446
00:34:27.480 --> 00:34:36.020
Ewan McGregor's acting has a campy quality
to it that reminds me of villain in a John

447
00:34:36.020 --> 00:34:44.600
Waters movie. Now, the queer community doesn’t
really like queer coded villains these days,

448
00:34:44.600 --> 00:34:51.919
which is pretty understandable. But in this
case, exceptions can and should be made. 

449
00:34:51.919 --> 00:34:56.240
Some of the Birds of Prey media discussion
was focused on how the film despises men or

450
00:34:56.240 --> 00:35:01.800
portrays white men as villains. That isn't
entirely accurate, but the film does have

451
00:35:01.800 --> 00:35:06.510
a slew of terrible men with a similar appearance.
What interests me about this is that Roman

452
00:35:06.510 --> 00:35:10.421
and Victor are examples of these evil men.
They aren't macho clichés of men, and they

453
00:35:10.421 --> 00:35:14.860
don't sexualize the female characters in the
film. Roman shifting into the Black Mask persona

454
00:35:14.860 --> 00:35:19.920
and forcing a woman to pull off her clothing
is one example where it doesn't feel like

455
00:35:19.920 --> 00:35:25.130
he's doing it for the sexual thrills, but
for the control. He also didn't want the dress

456
00:35:25.130 --> 00:35:29.950
in his club because it was a crime against
fashion. And unlike murder, some laws should

457
00:35:29.950 --> 00:35:35.320
never be broken. (but fashion has changed
- no it hasnt - serial mom clip)

458
00:35:35.320 --> 00:35:42.060
So is Black Mask GOOD representation of queer
men? No, of course not. But is he an interesting

459
00:35:42.060 --> 00:35:47.430
character with more going for him than just
being the gay character. Yes. And that’s

460
00:35:47.430 --> 00:35:53.890
what we need. We need characters who are MORE
than just the gay one.

461
00:35:53.890 --> 00:36:03.770
This puts me in a difficult situation, as
it may not be clear what I’m advocating

462
00:36:03.770 --> 00:36:08.840
for. On one hand, I’m praising various instances
of subtlety in media when it comes to queer

463
00:36:08.840 --> 00:36:13.000
representation, while condemning other attempts
to make more ‘overtly’ queer media. But

464
00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:17.810
what I’m saying is that we don’t necessarily
need to chose between one or the other.

465
00:36:17.810 --> 00:36:21.930
Our representation would get boring if we,
as a group, decided that there was only one

466
00:36:21.930 --> 00:36:26.840
way to represent us. In that case, it would
be a gross disservice to the vast range of

467
00:36:26.840 --> 00:36:31.430
diversity in the queer experience. There isn’t
one way to be queer — there isn’t even

468
00:36:31.430 --> 00:36:37.130
one way to be gay. But my problem with ‘explicit’
representation in modern media is that you

469
00:36:37.130 --> 00:36:41.170
wouldn’t know that from the way we are represented.

470
00:36:41.170 --> 00:36:46.690
Maybe in thise case, it’s best to focus
less on depicting queer instances—

471
00:36:46.690 --> 00:36:53.000
—and instead place that focus on depicting
queer experiences.

472
00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:57.540
Making sure we push queer characters into
fiction doesn’t seem to be having the desired

473
00:36:57.540 --> 00:37:04.140
effect of having our people and communities
seen. As the end result is a matter of taking

474
00:37:04.140 --> 00:37:08.300
queer characters and making their motives
and backgrounds indistinguishable from straight

475
00:37:08.300 --> 00:37:13.020
characters. Reminiscent of saying we deserve
gay marriage because we’re ‘just like’

476
00:37:13.020 --> 00:37:18.740
heterosexual couples. We aren’t. We have
different social experiences with society

477
00:37:18.740 --> 00:37:20.480
at large.

478
00:37:20.480 --> 00:37:26.960
Our coming-of-age experiences, as they fit
outside the projected norm, are not the norm.

479
00:37:26.960 --> 00:37:31.150
And depicting queer characters as being ‘straight
characters but gay’ is a disservice to the

480
00:37:31.150 --> 00:37:35.170
way that the process of self-discovery and
independence shapes us.

481
00:37:35.170 --> 00:37:40.810
We’re NOT like everyone else. And that’s
what we should be proud of. We’re not even

482
00:37:40.810 --> 00:37:45.290
always like each other — and it should be
our diversity that society at large values

483
00:37:45.290 --> 00:37:47.960
as our most significant strength.

484
00:37:47.960 --> 00:37:52.140
Not our ability to buy a house in the suburbs
in a prestigious school district.

485
00:37:52.140 --> 00:37:56.740
Because while we’re busy showing how much
gay people are ‘just like’ straight people,

486
00:37:56.740 --> 00:38:01.360
We’re forgetting about the boss-ass bitch
queers who have only ever found acceptance

487
00:38:01.360 --> 00:38:07.910
by being better than literally everyone else.
So much so that they can’t find where their

488
00:38:07.910 --> 00:38:10.860
performance ends and they begin.

489
00:38:10.860 --> 00:38:14.630
The angry queers who feel like they’re only
worth something if they’re validated by

490
00:38:14.630 --> 00:38:18.850
the established order, instead of finding
worth in themselves.

491
00:38:18.850 --> 00:38:23.320
And the personal improvement queers who struggle
to figure out what it is they have to offer

492
00:38:23.320 --> 00:38:24.320
the world.

493
00:38:24.320 --> 00:38:30.200
Our stories, our experiences, our lives are
interesting and relevant. And if you tell

494
00:38:30.200 --> 00:38:34.720
an interesting story about a queer person,
audiences will cheer for them.

495
00:38:34.720 --> 00:38:40.460
Which is what made me love this show. It represents
the queer community, specifically queer men,

496
00:38:40.460 --> 00:38:46.750
in a way that I very rarely see. And that
being... that there are many different types

497
00:38:46.750 --> 00:38:48.140
of queer people.

498
00:38:48.140 --> 00:38:52.620
Insecure ones like Yuri. Perfectionists like
Victor. People who want to be center stage,

499
00:38:52.620 --> 00:38:56.290
and people who just want to blend in. Those
of us who are comfortable in our skin, and

500
00:38:56.290 --> 00:39:01.120
those who are still working on things. Masculine
or Feminine. Supportive or Competitive. Tender

501
00:39:01.120 --> 00:39:08.100
or painfully horny. We come in many different
shapes and sizes. Skin colors, religious backgrounds,

502
00:39:08.100 --> 00:39:09.570
nationalities, and beliefs.

503
00:39:09.570 --> 00:39:15.820
But at our best, like the skaters in Yuri
on Ice, we are, at the end of the day, a community.

504
00:39:15.820 --> 00:39:20.510
There to help one another, and push each other
when we need it. So anytime you feel small

505
00:39:20.510 --> 00:39:27.320
or lost or ignored… like you’re not good
enough. Like you don’t fit in. Think about

506
00:39:27.320 --> 00:39:32.310
the queer people who came before us. The artists.
The politicians. The power brokers. The creators.

507
00:39:32.310 --> 00:39:38.580
The writers. The teachers. The brothers and
sisters. The good friends. Who changed things,

508
00:39:38.580 --> 00:39:42.590
who told stories, who made an impact.

509
00:39:42.590 --> 00:39:53.630
Because they’re important. We’re important,
we’re significant, and we were born to make

510
00:39:53.630 --> 00:39:53.829
history.